Threat Hunting > [T3]: Endpoint Hunting for Lateral Movement

Lateral movement refers to the process of moving from one compromised system to another within an organization's network. The objective of lateral movement is to gain access to sensitive information or expand the attacker's presence within the network. In this lesson, we will focus on hunting for lateral movement using PsExec as an example.

In this lesson, we will cover:

  • Methods attackers use for lateral movement
  • PsExec overview
  • Detecting PsExec activity in your network

 

Methods Attackers Use for Lateral Movement

Attackers can use various methods for lateral movement, including:

  • Pass the Hash: Using the hash value of a compromised user's password to authenticate to other systems without having the actual password.
  • Remote Execution Tools: Using tools such as PsExec or Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) to execute commands on remote systems.
  • Exploiting Vulnerabilities: Exploiting system or application vulnerabilities to gain access and move laterally within the network.
  • Using Stolen Credentials: Using stolen credentials, such as usernames and passwords, to move laterally within the network.
  • Application or Service Abuse: Abusing legitimate applications or services, such as Remote Procedure Call (RPC) or Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), for lateral movement.

PsExec Overview

PsExec is a legitimate tool often used by administrators to run processes on remote systems. However, attackers can also use PsExec to execute malicious code on a target system, making it crucial to detect its malicious use.

Detecting PsExec Activity in Your Network

There are several methods to detect PsExec activity, and we will focus on three of them:

Monitoring registry changes during PsExec execution on an endpoint: Look for Event ID 13 in Sysmon logs and any registry key ending with "EulaAccepted."

 

Analyzing process events when the PsExec binary is executed: Monitor process execution events (Event ID 1 in Sysmon) and filter for process names starting with "psexec."

 

Observing services created during remote PsExec execution on an endpoint: When PsExec executes remote commands on an endpoint, it creates a remote service on the remote endpoint. This service becomes a parent process for all other commands sent by the attacker to be executed on the remote system. Filter for processes with the default service name "PSEXESVC" as a parent process to identify commands executed remotely via PsExec.
